[[File:'Breakfast Buddha' by Allyn Bromley, 2004.JPG|thumb|right|250px|''Breakfast Buddha'' by '''Allyn Bromley''', 2004, color [[screen print]] with mixed-media hand work]]
'''Allyn Bromley''' (born 1928) is an American printmaker and art educator who was born in San Francisco. She first came to Hawaii in 1952, and subsequently moved to [[Waikiki]], where she lived for nine years. From 1961-1965, she lived in Europe, returning to Hawaii in 1965. She received a BFA from the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] in 1968 and an MFA from the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] in 1971.<ref>[http://www.mutualart.com/Exhibitions/Allyn-Bromley--Finding-Latitude/9680BC60744C7F46#Info Allyn Bromley: Finding Latitude, mutualart.com]</ref><ref>Zuern, John David, ''Finding Latitude: The Work of Allyn Bromley'', The Contemporary Museum, Honolulu, 2010, pp. 16-17</ref>
She began her teaching career at [[Leeward Community College]] in 1972, where she taught until 1983. She became director of the Printmaking Department at the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]] in 1983, and retired as a [[professor emeritus]] in 2000.<ref>[http://www.hawaii.edu/art/people/ University of Hawaii Art Department]</ref><ref>[http://blog.honoluluacademy.org/making-a-statement-allyn-bromley-on-her-works-green-piece-and-kakaako/ Honolulu Museum of Art blog]</ref><ref>Zuern, John David, ''Finding Latitude: The Work of Allyn Bromley'', The Contemporary Museum, Honolulu, 2010, p. 17</ref>
Bromley works primarily in [[screen printing]]. Since the late 1980s, she has been combining printing with painting, drawing, and [[Collage|collaging]].<ref>Zuern, John David, ''Finding Latitude: The Work of Allyn Bromley'', The Contemporary Museum, Honolulu, 2010, p. 9</ref> ''Breakfast Buddha'', from 2004, is an example of her mixed-media prints. As in much of her portrait work, the subject's silhouette is emphasized, and facial details are minimized.<ref>Zuern, John David, ''Finding Latitude: The Work of Allyn Bromley'', The Contemporary Museum, Honolulu, 2010, p. 10</ref> The [[Hawaii State Art Museum]] and the [[Honolulu Museum of Art]] are among the public collections holding work by '''Allyn Bromley'''.<ref>[http://www.mutualart.com/Exhibitions/Allyn-Bromley--Finding-Latitude/9680BC60744C7F46#Info Allyn Bromley: Finding Latitude, mutualart.com]</ref>
