{{unreferenced|date=February 2013}} {{About|the painting by de Chirico||Song of Love (disambiguation){{!}}Song of Love}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=De_Chirico's_Love_Song.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Love Song | artist=[[Giorgio de Chirico]] | year=1914 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=73 | width_metric=59.1 | height_imperial={{frac|28|3|4}} | width_imperial= {{frac|23|3|8}} | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[New York City]] | museum=[[Museum of Modern Art]] }}
'''''The Song of Love''''' (also known as '''''Le chant d'amour''''' or '''''Love Song'''''; 1914) is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Metaphysical art|metaphysical painter]] [[Giorgio de Chirico]]. It is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and an early example of the [[Surrealism|surrealist]] style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by [[André Breton]] in 1924.
It depicts an outdoor architectural setting similar to other works by de Chirico at this time. This time however, the main focus is a small wall on which is mounted a [[Ancient Greek sculpture|Greek sculpted]] head and a surgeon's glove. Below it is a green ball. On the horizon is the outline of a locomotive, an image that recurs several times during this period of de Chirico's career.
